00:43.340 --> 00:48.300
This is Daryl Lane and David Crews. Some of the most exciting science fiction being written today

00:48.300 --> 00:53.380
comes from the pen of Jack Chalker and it's clear that he's a popular writer too probably best known

00:53.380 --> 00:58.080
for the five books in the Well World series. In fact the first novel in that series Midnight at

00:58.080 --> 01:03.280
the Well of Souls has sold over a million copies. Chalker's first book came out not that long ago,

01:03.280 --> 01:08.960
1976, so his work is still fairly recent. He'd been active in the field though years before he started

01:08.960 --> 01:15.300
writing corresponding with authors and other fans, attending conventions, editing a fanzine, even

01:15.300 --> 01:20.520
starting a small publishing company Mirage Press to produce material on science fiction but Chalker

01:20.520 --> 01:26.240
says he'd always planned on being a writer. I'd always known I was going to be a writer. I mean

01:26.240 --> 01:30.840
there just was never any question in my mind but it was just sort of something that you never really

01:30.840 --> 01:37.080
sat down and did. I used to play around with stories here and there. Uh John Campbell was a big help

01:38.560 --> 01:44.220
uh during the 60s. I would float ideas and fragments off him and he would be very very nice

01:44.860 --> 01:51.560
and tell me exactly what was wrong. Of course what infuriated everybody about John Campbell uh was that

01:51.560 --> 01:57.120
uh the man had been editing for 40 years and he could put his finger on something and tell you exactly

01:57.120 --> 02:02.980
what you were doing wrong and it was terribly infuriating to discover that he was right in almost every case.

02:03.560 --> 02:14.180
Uh you saw why he did it from 39 until he died and uh as a result of being able to have the help of people

02:14.180 --> 02:20.280
like Campbell and August Derleth and a lot of really established writers and editors in the field,

02:20.280 --> 02:26.560
uh i was able to get a good recognition of exactly what was required in the field.

02:27.280 --> 02:33.560
Uh it just was a matter of sitting down and doing it. Fortunately he did sit down and do it

02:33.560 --> 02:44.440
publishing Jungle of Stars in 1976. So I sat on a typewriter and there was really no question in my mind as to

02:44.440 --> 02:53.020
uh what I do first. I had been playing around with an idea for years and years and years. There's even

02:53.020 --> 03:02.020
a short fanzine version of it 20 years old uh called Jungle or Jungle of Stars or uh there were a lot of

03:02.020 --> 03:11.400
code words but Jungle was always in it. And um I sat down and wrote the thing. I wrote. It had been around so

03:11.400 --> 03:19.000
long in my mind and discussions and so on that, there was just no problems no resistance no having to

03:19.000 --> 03:24.520
think it out or anything else. And I wrote it solidly in about two and a half three weeks

03:26.200 --> 03:37.260
and then sent it off. And it's a good old-fashioned type. It's a science fiction murder mystery

03:37.260 --> 03:44.280
uh very much very much very much at home in the old uh Astounding, Analogs and so on even though it

03:44.280 --> 03:46.780
does have some modern touches to it.

03:52.400 --> 03:56.400
Some of his earlier contacts with people in the field of science fiction paid off

03:56.400 --> 04:04.760
one of them Judy Lindal Ray bought the novel. Judy Lindal Ray uh who had just become editor of

04:04.760 --> 04:10.600
uh Ballantine, which was soon to have a science fiction line named after her,

04:12.360 --> 04:19.600
uh took a look at it we'd known each other for about 15 years. And uh she put off reading it for

04:19.600 --> 04:25.960
quite a long time because she was afraid that if it was terrible and she said so that you know she'd

04:25.960 --> 04:33.080
blow our friendship or something. Finally she said uh uh i we got together at a convention and she admitted

04:33.080 --> 04:38.220
to me all this she said okay I'll read it but be prepared and about four days later I get a phone

04:38.220 --> 04:44.240
call and she said hey this is great I want to buy it and that was the first sale.

04:45.980 --> 04:51.600
Since then Chalker has published some 13 novels and he's still going strong. More with Jack Chalker next

04:51.600 --> 04:51.980
time.

