This is the Science Ficiton Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.
And here are your hosts. This is David Crews and Daryl Lane.

06:32.680 --> 06:39.320
A hike through a national park and a war game board, unlikely sources for a tremendously popular science fiction novel.

06:39.560 --> 06:43.180
The novel is Midnight at the Well of Souls. The author is Jack Chalker.

06:43.340 --> 06:48.200
The book concerns the Well World, an artificial planet constructed by a vanished civilization.

06:48.500 --> 06:54.660
The Well World is divided into 1,560 separate environments. Separate worlds, really. Each

06:54.660 --> 06:57.260
with its own climate, geography, and intelligent inhabitants.

06:57.770 --> 07:01.600
Each division is shaped like a hexagon, and for that reason they're called hexes.

07:02.380 --> 07:07.000
Chalker was in an isolated village called Stehekin, on the shore of Lake Chelan in central Washington

07:07.000 --> 07:09.160
state, when he got the idea for the Well World.

07:10.680 --> 07:17.400
I got to sitting by the lake that night and talking with some people, and I got the idea

07:20.300 --> 07:27.220
for this large world built by a long dead race, and so on, and I didn't really have much of

07:27.220 --> 07:34.160
an idea of what it was, and they do have a service out of Stehekin that'll take you up to Trailhead.

07:35.300 --> 07:41.220
And so I went up to Trailhead, and I wound up walking down. I'm a great hiker as long as the

07:41.220 --> 07:47.140
direction's down. I'm afraid I've never been to the bottom of the Grand Canyon because I can get

07:47.140 --> 07:53.300
down there, but I can't get back up. But here was a trail that was tailor-made for me. It was down the

07:53.300 --> 08:04.160
Cascades all the way. So I took it, and it took about eight and a half hours to walk the whole distance.

08:06.800 --> 08:13.380
And during that time, you go through eight climate zones. You start off in the snow. You wind up in a

08:13.380 --> 08:20.320
rainforest. And some of the changes are rather abrupt. You just go around a switchback, and it

08:20.320 --> 08:26.780
just changes from one climate to another, each with its own different plants and insects and

08:27.360 --> 08:32.520
occasional mammals. Even the birds seem to be different. And I thought, yeah, this is how that

08:32.520 --> 08:39.100
big world would be like. So even though while I was on my way down, I was kind of scribbling ideas.

08:41.160 --> 08:50.040
And I got the idea for this giant world composed of basically worldlets, different abrupt geography,

08:50.300 --> 08:59.400
climate, landforms, you name it, each with its own dominant race. By the time I hit bottom, I had it

08:59.400 --> 09:04.420
pretty well worked out, although I didn't really know what the shape of the things were going to be.

09:05.880 --> 09:09.000
Back home in Maryland, he got some help on the shape of the well world.

09:10.240 --> 09:16.460
I was discussing the idea with a science fiction fan named Ben Yalow, son of the Nobel winner,

09:17.960 --> 09:22.740
Rosalyn Yalow. And he says, why don't you just use an Avalon Hill game board?

09:24.220 --> 09:32.760
And I thought, yeah, that would work. So we got out an Avalon Hill map, a war game map, and a little

09:32.760 --> 09:40.280
trusty calculator. We laid a grid of these hexagons around a roughly Earth-sized world.

09:40.860 --> 09:46.640
Of course, we cannot cover a sphere with hexagons. So that means we had the north zone and the south

09:46.640 --> 09:54.960
zone, which would be the embassy's entry and exit points that would cover our sphere. And then it was

09:54.960 --> 10:03.020
just simply a matter of sitting down, listing what was required to do, what kind of creatures and land

10:03.660 --> 10:10.440
climate and so on I would have to do for the route of the story, dropping by Avalon Hill, which I lived

10:10.440 --> 10:16.380
very near at the time, picking up some blank maps, and just working it out from there.

10:17.780 --> 10:22.300
What Chalker worked out turned into his best-known novel, Midnight at the Well of Souls.

10:22.300 --> 10:26.740
It was so popular that it went out of print a few months after its initial press run.

10:26.920 --> 10:31.100
And Chalker has added four novels since then, making a five-book series in the Well World.

10:31.360 --> 10:35.700
The whole thing turned out to be a colorful and exciting epic on the origin of the universe

10:35.700 --> 10:39.940
and all of the creatures in it. It should fascinate any reader of science fiction.

10:40.260 --> 10:41.960
More on Jack Chalker next time.

