12:21.520 --> 12:22.760
This is Daryl Lane.

12:22.960 --> 12:23.760
And David Crews.

12:24.080 --> 12:28.060
The five novels in Jack Chalker's Well World series are based on a familiar science fiction

12:28.060 --> 12:28.580
concept.

12:28.980 --> 12:33.920
And that concept is the notion of a long-dead race of superior beings whose artifacts are

12:33.920 --> 12:34.780
found by humans.

12:35.000 --> 12:38.980
But there are a couple of interesting twists given to this concept by Chalker.

12:39.320 --> 12:44.700
One twist is the principal artifact by the vanished race. It's a planet called the Well World.

12:44.700 --> 12:51.060
It's artificial. And its interior is a supercomputer that can transform matter into all sorts of living creatures.

12:51.400 --> 12:58.080
It's really a laboratory planet where species are created and tested before being transferred to various places throughout the universe.

12:58.080 --> 13:03.640
And the other twist is that these superior beings, called the Markovians, aren't actually gone.

13:03.940 --> 13:07.060
They just transform themselves into other, more primitive beings.

13:07.060 --> 13:09.360
Chalker talks about the Markovians.

13:10.040 --> 13:12.820
They got to the point where they were gods, literally.

13:14.040 --> 13:19.340
Where their devices could conjure up anything they wanted, just the mere thought of it.

13:21.080 --> 13:27.780
I sense that it pointed out to me that they're sort of like the Krell in the old movie Forbidden Planet,

13:28.360 --> 13:30.760
in that they reach this godhead status.

13:31.120 --> 13:37.000
But the Krell experiment failed, because they couldn't control their passions.

13:37.400 --> 13:41.460
And the Markovian experiment succeeded, and they literally became gods.

13:41.900 --> 13:43.160
Then they became miserable.

13:43.720 --> 13:45.620
There was nothing left to attain.

13:45.900 --> 13:47.480
There was nothing left to know.

13:47.480 --> 13:48.720
There was nothing left, you know.

13:49.280 --> 13:55.240
You got a bunch of creatures that spent millions of years rising to this point,

13:55.340 --> 13:57.060
and they sit around and they say, is this all there is?

13:58.340 --> 14:01.460
At this point, the Markovians decided to start all over again.

14:02.480 --> 14:08.600
The idea of the great experiment that came about was to redo it,

14:08.860 --> 14:12.480
to literally start the Markovians over from scratch,

14:13.260 --> 14:16.500
with different kinds of creatures, different environments,

14:18.660 --> 14:20.800
with no real value system.

14:21.040 --> 14:23.360
I mean, they have to develop their own unique value systems.

14:23.800 --> 14:24.580
They do.

14:25.520 --> 14:31.940
And as a result, they're grown and they're tested on this laboratory world, the well world.

14:32.260 --> 14:37.180
And then they were the ones that worked, the ones that showed promise of survival,

14:37.200 --> 14:43.360
were then set into motion out throughout the universe, including man.

14:45.620 --> 14:58.500
And they had the hopes that eventually one of these races would reach a state of perfection that would not be empty or hollow.

14:58.500 --> 15:05.480
Now, I personally believe that when you reach that state, it is empty and hollow.

15:06.220 --> 15:11.900
But that's just my feeling.

15:11.900 --> 15:14.620
Other people might certainly do think differently.

15:16.100 --> 15:21.500
The Markovians create hundreds of different species, all intelligent, but all incredibly different.

15:21.760 --> 15:25.460
We asked Chalker how he gets ideas for creating such a variety of aliens.

15:26.920 --> 15:28.860
I used a variety of things.

15:28.980 --> 15:35.580
In some cases, a good pictorial natural history text will give you more weird creatures than you've ever seen,

15:37.120 --> 15:38.660
which can be modified.

15:40.360 --> 15:41.900
Some came out of mythology.

15:44.140 --> 15:48.880
Some came more or less direct out of fantasia, sorts of like that.

15:49.820 --> 15:54.080
And a few came out of comic book concepts.

15:54.600 --> 16:00.740
And, you know, you just draw them in from all over and you use basic shapes and basic types.

16:01.120 --> 16:09.040
And then you adjust them to what would happen if these were real, sentient, intelligent creatures.

16:10.620 --> 16:17.340
I found very, very little trouble in coming up with an enormous variety of them.

16:17.940 --> 16:23.920
I'm not sure whether I could come up with 1,560, which is the number I would have to to visit every hex in the well world.

16:24.560 --> 16:27.440
But I've had no trouble coming up with the 200 or 300 so far.

16:28.220 --> 16:30.060
More with Jack Chalker next time.

